, who viewed exact segmentation as the ultimate goal. [CLS] [SEP] Therefore, we only score guess/gold pairs with identical character yields, a condition that allows us to measure parsing, tagging, and segmentation accuracy by ignoring whitespace. [CLS] [SEP] Table 9 shows that MADA produces a high quality segmentation, and that the effect of cascading segmentation errors on parsing is only 1.92% F1. [CLS] [SEP] However, MADA is language-specific and relies on manually constructed dictionaries. [CLS] [SEP] Conversely, the lattice parser requires no linguistic resources and produces segmentations of comparable quality. [CLS] [SEP] Nonetheless, parse quality is much lower in the joint model because a lattice is effectively a long sentence. [CLS] [SEP] A cell in the bottom row of the parse chart is required for each potential whitespace boundary. [CLS] [SEP] As we have said, parse quality decreases with sentence length. [CLS] [SEP] Finally, we note that simple weighting gives nearly a 2% F1 improvement, whereas Goldberg and Tsarfaty (2008) found that unweighted lattices were more effective for Hebrew. [CLS] [SEP] Table 9: Dev set results for sentences of length ≤ 70. [CLS] [SEP] Coverage indicates the fraction of hypotheses in which the character yield exactly matched the reference. [CLS] [SEP] Each model was able to produce hypotheses for all input sentences. [CLS] [SEP] In these experiments, the input lacks segmentation markers, hence the slightly different dev set baseline than in Table 6. [CLS] [SEP] By establishing significantly higher parsing baselines, we have shown that Arabic parsing performance is not as poor as previously thought, but remains much lower than English. [CLS] [SEP] We have described grammar state splits that significantly improve parsing performance, catalogued parsing errors, and quantified the effect of segmentation errors. [CLS] [SEP] With a human evaluation we also showed that ATB inter-annotator agreement remains low relative to the WSJ corpus. [CLS] [SEP] Our results suggest that current parsing models would benefit from better annotation consistency and enriched annotation in certain syntactic configurations. [CLS] [SEP] Acknowledgments We thank Steven Bethard, Evan Rosen, and Karen Shiells for material contributions to this work. [CLS] [SEP] We are also grateful to Markus Dickinson, Ali Farghaly, Nizar Habash, Seth Kulick, David McCloskey, Claude Reichard, Ryan Roth, and Reut Tsarfaty for constructive discussions. [CLS] [SEP] The first author is supported by a National Defense Science and Engineering Graduate (NDSEG) fellowship. [CLS] [SEP] This paper is based on work supported in part by DARPA through IBM. [CLS] [SEP] The content does not necessarily reflect the views of the U.S. Government, and no official endorsement should be inferred.